JUNE, 1992

OVARIAN CANCER

By Judith A. Johnson, Science Policy Research Division.  2 pages.
Ovarian cancer is the fourth leading cause of cancer mortality,
behind lung, breast, and colo-rectal.  The National Cancer Institute
(NCI) estimates that in 1992 13,000 women will die of ovarian cancer
and 21,000 new cases will be diagnosed.  Ovarian cancer is difficult
to diagnose because it often imitates other diseases.  Recent
research indicates that if it is detected early, a cure is possible.
NCI is supporting research in a number of institutions to evaluate
the usefulness of early screening methods in the detection of ovarian
cancer.  Order No. 92-280 SPR.

The full report, as described above and authored by the Congressional
Research Service, costs $47 from Penny Hill Press, 6440 Wiscasset
Road, Bethesda, MD  20816, 301-229-8229.



