<A NAME = "21"></A>Copyright
FEDERAL/INDUSTRY WATCHDOG via NewsNet
MAY, 1991

POSTAL SERVICE:  CONTRACTOR PERFORMANCE--EXPRESS AND
PRIORITY MAIL TRANSPORTATION

Order No.:  GAO/GGD-91-13
Pages:  4

GAO reviewed the Postal Service's award of an express and
priority mail transportation contract to Air Train, Inc.
(later renamed Emery Worldwide Airline, Inc.) and the
contractor's performance under that contract.  The contract
says that the minimum acceptable performance for meeting
express and priority mail delivery times at destination
cities is 98 percent of the time. GAO found that after the
initial start-up week, the on-time performance requirement
was met for 54 of 57 weeks. In addition to the on-time
requirement, the contractor is expected to deliver all
express and priority mail to destination cities without
leaving any mail behind, either at the originating city or
at the hub (where the mail is sorted). GAO found that Air
Train failed to meet these standards 10 out of 57 weeks.

The above-described report is available free from the U.S.
General Accounting Office, P.O. Box 6015, Gaithersburg, MD
20877, 202-275-6241.



